# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: oscillator-circuits
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] A **Colpitts oscillator**, invented in 1918 by Canadian-American engineer Edwin H.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] Colpitts using vacuum tubes, is one of a number of designs for LC oscillators, electronic oscillators that use a combination of inductors (L) and capacitors (C) to produce an oscillation at a certain frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The distinguishing feature of the Colpitts oscillator is that the feedback for the active device is taken from a voltage divider made of two capacitors in series across the inductor.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The amplifier will have differing input and output impedances, and these need to be coupled into the LC circuit without overly damping it.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] A Colpitts oscillator uses a pair of capacitors to provide voltage division to couple the energy in and out of the tuned circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] (It can be considered as the electrical dual of a Hartley oscillator, where the feedback signal is taken from an "inductive" voltage divider consisting of two coils in series (or a tapped coil).) Fig.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] 1 shows the common-base Colpitts circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The inductor *L* and the series combination of *C*1 and *C*2 form the resonant tank circuit, which determines the frequency of the oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The voltage across *C*2 is applied to the base-emitter junction of the transistor, as feedback to create oscillations.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] Here the voltage across *C*1 provides feedback.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The actual frequency of oscillation will be slightly lower due to junction capacitances and resistive loading of the transistor.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] As with any oscillator, the amplification of the active component should be marginally larger than the attenuation of the resonator losses and its voltage division, to obtain stable operation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] Thus, a Colpitts oscillator used as a variable-frequency oscillator (VFO) performs best when a variable inductance is used for tuning, as opposed to tuning just one of the two capacitors.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] If tuning by variable capacitor is needed, it should be done with a third capacitor connected in parallel to the inductor (or in series as in the Clapp oscillator).
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] 3 shows an example with component values.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] Instead of field-effect transistors, other active components such as bipolar junction transistors or vacuum tubes, capable of producing gain at the desired frequency, could be used.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The common gate amplifier has a low input impedance and a high output impedance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] Therefore, the amplifier input, the source, is connected to the low impedance tap of the LC circuit L1, C1, C2, C3 and the amplifier output, the drain, is connected to the high impedance top of the LC circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The resistor R1 sets the operating point to 0.5mA drain current with no oscillating.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The output is at the low impedance tap and can drive some load.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] Still, this circuit has low harmonic distortion.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] An additional variable capacitor between drain of J1 and ground allows to change the frequency of the circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The load resistor RL is part of the simulation, not part of the circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] One method of oscillator analysis is to determine the input impedance of an input port neglecting any reactive components.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] If the impedance yields a negative resistance term, oscillation is possible.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] This method will be used here to determine conditions of oscillation and the frequency of oscillation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] This configuration models the common collector circuit in the section above.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] For initial analysis, parasitic elements and device non-linearities will be ignored.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] These terms can be included later in a more rigorous analysis.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] Even with these approximations, acceptable comparison with experimental results is possible.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] where $v_{1}$ is the input voltage, and $i_{1}$ is the input current.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] where $g_{m}$ is the transconductance of the transistor.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] If $Z_{1}$ and $Z_{2}$ are complex and of the same sign, then $R_{\text{in}}$ will be a negative resistance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] If an inductor is connected to the input, then the circuit will oscillate if the magnitude of the negative resistance is greater than the resistance of the inductor and any stray elements.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The frequency of oscillation is as given in the previous section.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] For the example oscillator above, the emitter current is roughly 1 mA.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] This value should be sufficient to overcome any positive resistance in the circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] By inspection, oscillation is more likely for larger values of transconductance and smaller values of capacitance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] A more complicated analysis of the common-base oscillator reveals that a low-frequency amplifier voltage gain must be at least 4 to achieve oscillation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] If the two capacitors are replaced by inductors, and magnetic coupling is ignored, the circuit becomes a Hartley oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] In the Hartley circuit, oscillation is more likely for larger values of transconductance and larger values of inductance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The above analysis also describes the behavior of the Pierce oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The Pierce oscillator, with two capacitors and one inductor, is equivalent to the Colpitts oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] Equivalence can be shown by choosing the junction of the two capacitors as the ground point.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] An electrical dual of the standard Pierce oscillator using two inductors and one capacitor is equivalent to the Hartley oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] A Colpitts oscillator is an electronic circuit that generates a sinusoidal waveform, typically in the radio frequency range.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] It uses an inductor and two capacitors in parallel to form a resonant tank circuit, which determines the oscillation frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The output signal from the tank circuit is fed back into the input of an amplifier, where it is amplified and fed back into the tank circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The feedback signal provides the necessary phase shift for sustained oscillation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The Colpitts oscillator is widely used in various applications, such as RF communication systems, signal generators, and electronic testing equipment.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] It has better frequency stability than the Hartley oscillator, which uses a tapped inductor instead of a tapped capacitor in the tank circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] However, the Colpitts oscillator may require a higher supply voltage and a larger coupling capacitor than the Hartley oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] The amplitude of oscillation is generally difficult to predict, but it can often be accurately estimated using the describing function method.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] where $I_{C}$ is the bias current, and $R_{L}$ is the load resistance at the collector.
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] This assumes that the transistor does not saturate, the collector current flows in narrow pulses, and that the output voltage is sinusoidal (low distortion).
[src:oscillator-circuits/colpitts-oscillator] This approximate result also applies to oscillators employing different active device, such as MOSFETs and vacuum tubes.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A **crystal oscillator** is an electronic oscillator circuit that uses a piezoelectric crystal as a frequency-selective element.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The oscillator frequency is often used to keep track of time, as in quartz wristwatches, to provide a stable clock signal for digital integrated circuits, and to stabilize frequencies for radio transmitters and receivers.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The most common type of piezoelectric resonator used is a quartz crystal, so oscillator circuits incorporating them became known as crystal oscillators.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] However, other piezoelectric materials including polycrystalline ceramics are used in similar circuits.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A crystal oscillator relies on the slight change in shape of a quartz crystal under an electric field, a property known as inverse piezoelectricity.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A voltage applied to the electrodes on the crystal causes it to change shape; when the voltage is removed, the crystal generates a small voltage as it elastically returns to its original shape.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The quartz oscillates at a stable resonant frequency (relative to other low-priced oscillators) with frequency accuracy measured in parts per million (ppm).
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] It behaves like an RLC circuit, but with a much higher Q factor (lower energy loss on each cycle of oscillation and higher frequency selectivity) than can be reliably achieved with discrete capacitors (C) and inductors (L), which suffer from parasitic resistance (R).
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Once a quartz crystal is adjusted to a particular frequency (which is affected by the mass of electrodes attached to the crystal, the orientation of the crystal, temperature and other factors), it maintains that frequency with high stability.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Quartz crystals are manufactured for frequencies from a few tens of kilohertz to hundreds of megahertz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] As of 2003, around two billion crystals were manufactured annually.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Most are used for consumer devices such as wristwatches, clocks, radios, computers, and cellphones.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] However, in applications where small size and weight is needed crystals can be replaced by thin-film bulk acoustic resonators, specifically if ultra-high frequency (more than roughly 1.5 GHz) resonance is needed.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Quartz crystals are also found inside test and measurement equipment, such as counters, signal generators, and oscilloscopes.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A crystal oscillator is an electric oscillator type circuit that uses a piezoelectric resonator, a crystal, as its frequency-determining element.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] *Crystal* is the common term used in electronics for the frequency-determining component, a wafer of quartz crystal or ceramic with electrodes connected to it.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A more accurate term for "crystal" is *piezoelectric resonator*.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals are also used in other types of electronic circuits, such as crystal filters.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Piezoelectric resonators are sold as separate components for use in crystal oscillator circuits.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] They are also often incorporated in a single package with the crystal oscillator circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Piezoelectricity was discovered by Jacques and Pierre Curie in 1880.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Paul Langevin first investigated quartz resonators for use in sonar during World War I.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The first crystal-controlled oscillator, using a crystal of Rochelle salt, was built in 1917 and patented in 1918 by Alexander M.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Nicolson at Western Electric, although his priority was disputed by Walter Guyton Cady.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Cady built the first quartz crystal oscillator in 1921.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Other early innovators in quartz crystal oscillators include G.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Quartz crystal oscillators were developed for high-stability frequency references during the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Prior to crystals, radio stations controlled their frequency with tuned circuits, which could easily drift off frequency by 3–4 kHz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Since broadcast stations were assigned frequencies only 10 kHz (Americas) or 9 kHz (elsewhere) apart, interference between adjacent stations due to frequency drift was a common problem.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] In 1925, Westinghouse installed a crystal oscillator in its flagship station KDKA, and by 1926, quartz crystals were used to control the frequency of many broadcasting stations and were popular with amateur radio operators.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] In 1928, Warren Marrison of Bell Laboratories developed the first quartz-crystal clock.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] With accuracies of up to 1 second in 30 years (30 ms/y, or 0.95 ns/s), quartz clocks replaced precision pendulum clocks as the world's most accurate timekeepers until atomic clocks were developed in the 1950s.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Using the early work at Bell Laboratories, American Telephone and Telegraph Company (AT&T) eventually established their Frequency Control Products division, later spun off and known today as Vectron International.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] In 1933, Issac Koga of the Tokyo Institute of Technology reported the R1-cut quartz plate, a temperature-insensitive orientation with a near-zero frequency-temperature coefficient.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Koga-cut crystals were first used in radio transmitters and later in clocks, and the work was recognized as an IEEE Milestone in 2017.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A number of firms started producing quartz crystals for electronic use during this time.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Using what are now considered primitive methods, about 100,000 crystal units were produced in the United States during 1939.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Through World War II crystals were made from natural quartz crystal, virtually all from Brazil.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] By the 1970s virtually all crystals used in electronics were synthetic.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] In 1968, Juergen Staudte invented a photolithographic process for manufacturing quartz crystal oscillators while working at North American Aviation (now Rockwell) that allowed them to be made small enough for portable products like watches.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Although crystal oscillators still most commonly use quartz crystals, devices using other materials are becoming more common, such as ceramic resonators.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A crystal is a solid in which the constituent atoms, molecules, or ions are packed in a regularly ordered, repeating pattern extending in all three spatial dimensions.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Almost any object made of an elastic material could be used like a crystal, with appropriate transducers, since all objects have natural resonant frequencies of vibration.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] For example, steel is very elastic and has a high speed of sound.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] It was often used in mechanical filters before quartz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The resonant frequency depends on size, shape, elasticity, and the speed of sound in the material.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] High-frequency crystals are typically cut in the shape of a simple rectangle or circular disk.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Low-frequency crystals, such as those used in digital watches, are typically cut in the shape of a tuning fork.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] For applications not needing very precise timing, a low-cost ceramic resonator is often used in place of a quartz crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] When a crystal of quartz is properly cut and mounted, it can be made to distort in an electric field by applying a voltage to an electrode near or on the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] This property is known as inverse piezoelectricity.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] When the field is removed, the quartz generates an electric field as it returns to its previous shape, and this can generate a voltage.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The result is that a quartz crystal behaves like an RLC circuit, composed of an inductor, capacitor and resistor, with a precise resonant frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Quartz has the further advantage that its elastic constants and its size change in such a way that the frequency dependence on temperature can be very low.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The specific characteristics depend on the mode of vibration and the angle at which the quartz is cut (relative to its crystallographic axes).
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Therefore, the resonant frequency of the plate, which depends on its size, does not change much.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] This means that a quartz clock, filter or oscillator remains accurate.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] For critical applications the quartz oscillator is mounted in a temperature-controlled container, called a crystal oven, and can also be mounted on shock absorbers to prevent perturbation by external mechanical vibrations.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A quartz crystal can be modeled as an electrical network with low-impedance (series) and high-impedance (parallel) resonance points spaced closely together.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] where s is the complex frequency ( $s=j\omega$ ), $\omega _{\mathrm {s} }$ is the series resonant angular frequency, and $\omega _{\mathrm {p} }$ is the parallel resonant angular frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Adding capacitance across a crystal causes the (parallel) resonant frequency to decrease.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Adding inductance across a crystal causes the (parallel) resonant frequency to increase.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] These effects can be used to adjust the frequency at which a crystal oscillates.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystal manufacturers normally cut and trim their crystals to have a specified resonant frequency with a known "load" capacitance added to the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] For example, a crystal intended for a 6 pF load has its specified parallel resonant frequency when a 6.0 pF capacitor is placed across it.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Without the load capacitance, the resonant frequency is higher.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A quartz crystal provides both series and parallel resonance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The series resonance is a few kilohertz lower than the parallel one.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals below 30 MHz are generally operated between series and parallel resonance, which means that the crystal appears as an inductive reactance in operation, this inductance forming a parallel resonant circuit with externally connected parallel capacitance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Any small additional capacitance in parallel with the crystal pulls the frequency lower.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Moreover, the effective inductive reactance of the crystal can be reduced by adding a capacitor in series with the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] This latter technique can provide a useful method of trimming the oscillatory frequency within a narrow range; in this case inserting a capacitor in series with the crystal raises the frequency of oscillation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] For a crystal to operate at its specified frequency, the electronic circuit has to be exactly that specified by the crystal manufacturer.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Note that these points imply a subtlety concerning crystal oscillators in this frequency range: the crystal does not usually oscillate at precisely either of its resonant frequencies.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals above 30 MHz (up to >200 MHz) are generally operated at series resonance where the impedance appears at its minimum and equal to the series resistance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] For these crystals the series resistance is specified (<100 Ω) instead of the parallel capacitance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] To reach higher frequencies, a crystal can be made to vibrate at one of its overtone modes, which occur near multiples of the fundamental resonant frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Such a crystal is referred to as a 3rd, 5th, or even 7th overtone crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] To accomplish this, the oscillator circuit usually includes additional LC circuits to select the desired overtone.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A crystal's frequency characteristic depends on the shape or "cut" of the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A tuning-fork crystal is usually cut such that its frequency dependence on temperature is quadratic with the maximum around 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] This means that a tuning-fork crystal oscillator resonates close to its target frequency at room temperature, but slows when the temperature either increases or decreases from room temperature.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The crystal oscillator circuit sustains oscillation by taking a voltage signal from the quartz resonator, amplifying it, and feeding it back to the resonator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The rate of expansion and contraction of the quartz is the resonant frequency, and is determined by the cut and size of the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] When the energy of the generated output frequencies matches the losses in the circuit, an oscillation can be sustained.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] An oscillator crystal has two electrically conductive plates, with a slice or tuning fork of quartz crystal sandwiched between them.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] During startup, the controlling circuit places the crystal into an unstable equilibrium, and due to the positive feedback in the system, any tiny fraction of noise is amplified, ramping up the oscillation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The crystal resonator can also be seen as a highly frequency-selective filter in this system: it only passes a very narrow subband of frequencies around the resonant one, attenuating everything else.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Eventually, only the resonant frequency is active.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] As the oscillator amplifies the signals coming out of the crystal, the signals in the crystal's frequency band becomes stronger, eventually dominating the output of the oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The narrow resonance band of the quartz crystal filters out the unwanted frequencies.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The output frequency of a quartz oscillator can be either that of the fundamental resonance or of a multiple of that resonance, called a harmonic frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Harmonics are an exact integer multiple of the fundamental frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] But, like many other mechanical resonators, crystals exhibit several modes of oscillation, usually at approximately odd integer multiples of the fundamental frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] These are termed "overtone modes", and oscillator circuits can be designed to excite them.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The overtone modes are at frequencies which are approximate, but not exact odd integer multiples of that of the fundamental mode, and overtone frequencies are therefore not exact harmonics of the fundamental.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] High frequency crystals are often designed to operate at third, fifth, or seventh overtones.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Manufacturers have difficulty producing crystals thin enough to produce fundamental frequencies over 30 MHz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A fundamental crystal oscillator circuit is simpler and more efficient and has more pullability than a third overtone circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Depending on the manufacturer, the highest available fundamental frequency may be 25 MHz to 66 MHz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A major reason for the wide use of crystal oscillators is their high Q factor.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A typical *Q* value for a quartz oscillator ranges from 104 to 106, compared to perhaps 102 for an LC oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The maximum *Q* for a high stability quartz oscillator can be estimated as *Q* = 1.6 × 107/*f*, where *f* is the resonant frequency in megahertz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] One of the most important traits of quartz crystal oscillators is that they can exhibit very low phase noise.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] In many oscillators, any spectral energy at the resonant frequency is amplified by the oscillator, resulting in a collection of tones at different phases.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] In a crystal oscillator, the crystal mostly vibrates in one axis, therefore only one phase is dominant.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] This property of low phase noise makes them particularly useful in telecommunications where stable signals are needed, and in scientific equipment where very precise time references are needed.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Environmental changes of temperature, humidity, pressure, and vibration can change the resonant frequency of a quartz crystal, but there are several designs that reduce these environmental effects.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] These include the TCXO, MCXO, and OCXO which are defined below.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] These designs, particularly the OCXO, often produce devices with excellent short-term stability.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The limitations in short-term stability are due mainly to noise from electronic components in the oscillator circuits.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Long-term stability is limited by aging of the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Due to aging and environmental factors (such as temperature and vibration), it is difficult to keep even the best quartz oscillators within one part in 1010 of their nominal frequency without constant adjustment.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] For this reason, atomic oscillators are used for applications requiring better long-term stability and accuracy.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] For crystals operated at series resonance or pulled away from the main mode by the inclusion of a series inductor or capacitor, significant (and temperature-dependent) spurious responses may be experienced.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Though most spurious modes are typically some tens of kilohertz above the wanted series resonance, their temperature coefficient is different from the main mode, and the spurious response may move through the main mode at certain temperatures.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Even if the series resistances at the spurious resonances appear higher than the one at the wanted frequency, a rapid change in the main mode series resistance can occur at specific temperatures when the two frequencies are coincidental.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A consequence of these activity dips is that the oscillator may lock at a spurious frequency at specific temperatures.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] This is generally minimized by ensuring that the maintaining circuit has insufficient gain to activate unwanted modes.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Spurious frequencies are also generated by subjecting the crystal to vibration.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] This modulates the resonant frequency to a small degree by the frequency of the vibrations.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] SC-cut (Stress Compensated) crystals are designed to minimize the frequency effect of mounting stress and they are therefore less sensitive to vibration.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Acceleration effects including gravity are also reduced with SC-cut crystals, as is frequency change with time due to long term mounting stress variation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] There are disadvantages with SC-cut shear mode crystals, such as the need for the maintaining oscillator to discriminate against other closely related unwanted modes and increased frequency change due to temperature when subject to a full ambient range.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] SC-cut crystals are most advantageous where temperature control at their temperature of zero temperature coefficient (turnover) is possible, under these circumstances an overall stability performance from premium units can approach the stability of rubidium frequency standards.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals can be manufactured for oscillation over a wide range of frequencies, from a few kilohertz up to several hundred megahertz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Many applications call for a crystal oscillator frequency conveniently related to some other desired frequency, so hundreds of standard crystal frequencies are made in large quantities and stocked by electronics distributors.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] For example 3.579545 MHz crystals, which were made in large quantities for NTSC color television receivers, are now popular for many non-television applications (although most modern television receivers now use other frequency crystals for the color decoder).
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Using frequency dividers, frequency multipliers and phase-locked loop circuits, it is practical to derive a wide range of frequencies from one reference frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The most common material for oscillator crystals is quartz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] At the beginning of the technology, natural quartz crystals were used but now synthetic crystalline quartz grown by hydrothermal synthesis is predominant due to higher purity, lower cost and more convenient handling.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] One of the few remaining uses of natural crystals is for pressure transducers in deep wells.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] During World War II and for some time afterwards, natural quartz was considered a strategic material by the USA.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Large crystals were imported from Brazil.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Raw "lascas", the source material quartz for hydrothermal synthesis, are imported to USA or mined locally by Coleman Quartz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The average value of as-grown synthetic quartz in 1994 was 60 USD/kg.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Two types of quartz crystals exist: left-handed and right-handed.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The two differ in their optical rotation but they are identical in other physical properties.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Both left and right-handed crystals can be used for oscillators, if the cut angle is correct.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] In manufacture, right-handed quartz is generally used.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The SiO4 tetrahedrons form parallel helices; the direction of twist of the helix determines the left- or right-hand orientation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The helixes are aligned along the c-axis and merged, sharing atoms.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The mass of the helixes forms a mesh of small and large channels parallel to the c-axis.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The large ones are large enough to allow some mobility of smaller ions and molecules through the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] At 573 °C at 1 atmosphere (and at higher temperatures and higher pressures) the α-quartz undergoes quartz inversion, transforms reversibly to β-quartz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The reverse process however is not entirely homogeneous and crystal twinning occurs.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Care must be taken during manufacturing and processing to avoid phase transformation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Other phases, e.g. the higher-temperature phases tridymite and cristobalite, are not significant for oscillators.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] All quartz oscillator crystals are the α-quartz type.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Infrared spectrophotometry is used as one of the methods for measuring the quality of the grown crystals.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The measured value is based on the absorption bands of the OH radical and the infrared Q value is calculated.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The electronic grade crystals, grade C, have Q of 1.8 million or above; the premium grade B crystals have Q of 2.2 million, and special premium grade A crystals have Q of 3.0 million.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The Q value is calculated only for the z region; crystals containing other regions can be adversely affected.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Another quality indicator is the etch channel density; when the crystal is etched, tubular channels are created along linear defects.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] For processing involving etching, e.g. the wristwatch tuning fork crystals, low etch channel density is desirable.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The etch channel density for swept quartz is about 10–100 and significantly more for unswept quartz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Presence of etch channels and etch pits degrades the resonator's Q and introduces nonlinearities.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Quartz crystals can be grown for specific purposes.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals for AT-cut are the most common in mass production of oscillator materials; the shape and dimensions are optimized for high yield of the required wafers.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] High-purity quartz crystals are grown with especially low content of aluminium, alkali metal and other impurities and minimal defects; the low amount of alkali metals provides increased resistance to ionizing radiation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals for wrist watches, for cutting the tuning fork 32768 Hz crystals, are grown with very low etch channel density.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals for SAW devices are grown as flat, with large X-size seed with low etch channel density.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Special high-Q crystals, for use in highly stable oscillators, are grown at constant slow speed and have constant low infrared absorption along the entire Z axis.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals can be grown as Y-bar, with a seed crystal in bar shape and elongated along the Y axis, or as Z-plate, grown from a plate seed with Y-axis direction length and X-axis width.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The region around the seed crystal contains a large number of crystal defects and should not be used for the wafers.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals grow anisotropically; the growth along the Z axis is up to 3 times faster than along the X axis.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The growth direction and rate also influences the rate of uptake of impurities.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Y-bar crystals, or Z-plate crystals with long Y axis, have four growth regions usually called +X, −X, Z, and S.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The distribution of impurities during growth is uneven; different growth areas contain different levels of contaminants.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The Z regions are the purest, the small occasionally present S regions are less pure, the +X region is yet less pure, and the -X region has the highest level of impurities.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The impurities have a negative impact on radiation hardness, susceptibility to twinning, filter loss, and long and short term stability of the crystals.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Different-cut seeds in different orientations may provide other kinds of growth regions.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The growth speed of the −X direction is slowest due to the effect of adsorption of water molecules on the crystal surface; aluminium impurities suppress growth in two other directions.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The content of aluminium is lowest in Z region, higher in +X, yet higher in −X, and highest in S; the size of S regions also grows with increased amount of aluminium present.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The content of hydrogen is lowest in Z region, higher in +X region, yet higher in S region, and highest in −X.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Aluminium inclusions transform into color centers with gamma-ray irradiation, causing a darkening of the crystal proportional to the dose and level of impurities; the presence of regions with different darkness reveals the different growth regions.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The dominant type of defect of concern in quartz crystals is the substitution of an Al(III) for a Si(IV) atom in the crystal lattice.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The aluminium ion has an associated interstitial charge compensator present nearby, which can be a H+ ion (attached to the nearby oxygen and forming a hydroxyl group, called Al−OH defect), Li+ ion, Na+ ion, K+ ion (less common), or an electron hole trapped in a nearby oxygen atom orbital.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The composition of the growth solution, whether it is based on lithium or sodium alkali compounds, determines the charge compensating ions for the aluminium defects.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The ion impurities are of concern as they are not firmly bound and can migrate through the crystal, altering the local lattice elasticity and the resonant frequency of the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Other common impurities of concern are e.g. iron(III) (interstitial), fluorine, boron(III), phosphorus(V) (substitution), titanium(IV) (substitution, universally present in magmatic quartz, less common in hydrothermal quartz), and germanium(IV) (substitution).
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Sodium and iron ions can cause inclusions of acnite and elemeusite crystals.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Inclusions of water may be present in fast-grown crystals; interstitial water molecules are abundant near the crystal seed.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Another defect of importance is the hydrogen containing growth defect, when instead of a Si−O−Si structure, a pair of Si−OH HO−Si groups is formed; essentially a hydrolyzed bond.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Fast-grown crystals contain more hydrogen defects than slow-grown ones.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] These growth defects source as supply of hydrogen ions for radiation-induced processes and forming Al-OH defects.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Germanium impurities tend to trap electrons created during irradiation; the alkali metal cations then migrate towards the negatively charged center and form a stabilizing complex.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Matrix defects can also be present; oxygen vacancies, silicon vacancies (usually compensated by 4 hydrogens or 3 hydrogens and a hole), peroxy groups, etc.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Some of the defects produce localized levels in the forbidden band, serving as charge traps; Al(III) and B(III) typically serve as hole traps while electron vacancies, titanium, germanium, and phosphorus atoms serve as electron traps.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The trapped charge carriers can be released by heating; their recombination is the cause of thermoluminescence.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The mobility of interstitial ions depends strongly on temperature.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Hydrogen ions are mobile down to 10 K, but alkali metal ions become mobile only at temperatures around and above 200 K.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The hydroxyl defects can be measured by near-infrared spectroscopy.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The trapped holes can be measured by electron spin resonance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The Al−Na+ defects show as an acoustic loss peak due to their stress-induced motion; the Al−Li+ defects do not form a potential well so are not detectable this way.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Some of the radiation-induced defects during their thermal annealing produce thermoluminescence; defects related to aluminium, titanium, and germanium can be distinguished.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Swept crystals are crystals that have undergone a solid-state electrodiffusion purification process.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Sweeping involves heating the crystal above 500 °C in a hydrogen-free atmosphere, with a voltage gradient of at least 1 kV/cm, for several hours (usually over 12).
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The migration of impurities and the gradual replacement of alkali metal ions with hydrogen (when swept in air) or electron holes (when swept in vacuum) causes a weak electric current through the crystal; decay of this current to a constant value signals the end of the process.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The crystal is then left to cool, while the electric field is maintained.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The impurities are concentrated at the cathode region of the crystal, which is cut off afterwards and discarded.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Swept crystals have increased resistance to radiation, as the dose effects are dependent on the level of alkali metal impurities; they are suitable for use in devices exposed to ionizing radiation, e.g. for nuclear and space technology.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Sweeping under vacuum at higher temperatures and higher field strengths yields yet more radiation-hard crystals.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The level and character of impurities can be measured by infrared spectroscopy.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Quartz can be swept in both α and β phase; sweeping in β phase is faster, but the phase transition may induce twinning.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Twinning can be mitigated by subjecting the crystal to compression stress in the X direction, or an AC or DC electric field along the X axis while the crystal cools through the phase transformation temperature region.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Sweeping can also be used to introduce one kind of an impurity into the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Lithium, sodium, and hydrogen swept crystals are used for, e.g., studying quartz behavior.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Very small crystals for high fundamental-mode frequencies can be manufactured by photolithography.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals can be adjusted to exact frequencies by laser trimming.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Another method commonly used is electrochemical increase or decrease of silver electrode thickness by submerging a resonator in lapis lazuli dissolved in water, citric acid in water, or water with salt, and using the resonator as one electrode, and a small silver electrode as the other.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] By choosing the direction of current one can either increase or decrease the mass of the electrodes.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Details were published in "Radio" magazine (3/1978) by UB5LEV.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Raising frequency by scratching off parts of the electrodes is not advised as this may damage the crystal and lower its Q factor.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Capacitor trimmers can be also used for frequency adjustment of the oscillator circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Some other piezoelectric materials than quartz can be employed.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Some materials may be more suitable for specific applications.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] An oscillator crystal can be also manufactured by depositing the resonator material on the silicon chip surface.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals of gallium phosphate, langasite, langanite and langatate are about 10 times more pullable than the corresponding quartz crystals, and are used in some VCXO oscillators.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The frequency stability is determined by the crystal's quality factor (Q factor).
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] It is inversely dependent on the frequency, and on the constant that is dependent on the particular cut.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The stability of AT cut crystals decreases with increasing frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] For more accurate higher frequencies it is better to use a crystal with lower fundamental frequency, operating at an overtone.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A badly designed oscillator circuit may suddenly begin oscillating on an overtone.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] In 1972, a train in Fremont, California crashed due to a faulty oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] An inappropriate value of the tank capacitor caused the crystal in a control board to be overdriven, jumping to an overtone, and causing the train to speed up instead of slowing down.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Temperature influences the operating frequency; various forms of compensation are used, from analog compensation (TCXO) and microcontroller compensation (MCXO) to stabilization of the temperature with a crystal oven (OCXO).
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The crystals possess temperature hysteresis; the frequency at a given temperature achieved by increasing the temperature is not equal to the frequency on the same temperature achieved by decreasing the temperature.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The temperature sensitivity depends primarily on the cut; the temperature compensated cuts are chosen as to minimize frequency/temperature dependence.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Special cuts can be made with linear temperature characteristics; the LC cut is used in quartz thermometers.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Other influencing factors are the overtone used, the mounting and electrodes, impurities in the crystal, mechanical strain, crystal geometry, rate of temperature change, thermal history (due to hysteresis), ionizing radiation, and drive level.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals tend to suffer anomalies in their frequency/temperature and resistance/temperature characteristics, known as activity dips.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] These are small downward frequency or upward resistance excursions localized at certain temperatures, with their temperature position dependent on the value of the load capacitors.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Mechanical stresses also influence the frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Other dynamic stress inducing factors are shocks, vibrations, and acoustic noise.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Some cuts are less sensitive to stresses; the SC (stress-compensated) cut is an example.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Atmospheric pressure changes can also introduce deformations to the housing, influencing the frequency by changing stray capacitances.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Atmospheric humidity influences the thermal transfer properties of air, and can change electrical properties of plastics by diffusion of water molecules into their structure, altering the dielectric constants and electrical conductivity.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Other factors influencing the frequency are the power supply voltage, load impedance, magnetic fields, electric fields (in case of cuts that are sensitive to them, e.g., SC cuts), the presence and absorbed dose of γ-particles and ionizing radiation, and the age of the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals undergo slow gradual change of frequency with time, known as aging.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The mounting and contacts may undergo relief of the built-in stresses.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Molecules of contamination either from the residual atmosphere, outgassed from the crystal, electrodes or packaging materials, or introduced during sealing the housing can be adsorbed on the crystal surface, changing its mass; this effect is exploited in quartz crystal microbalances.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The composition of the crystal can be gradually altered by outgassing, diffusion of atoms of impurities or migrating from the electrodes, or the lattice can be damaged by radiation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Slow chemical reactions may occur on or in the crystal, or on the inner surfaces of the enclosure.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Electrode material, e.g. chromium or aluminium, can react with the crystal, creating layers of metal oxide and silicon; these interface layers can undergo changes in time.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The pressure in the enclosure can change due to varying atmospheric pressure, temperature, leaks, or outgassing of the materials inside.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Factors outside of the crystal itself are e.g. aging of the oscillator circuitry (and e.g. change of capacitances), and drift of parameters of the crystal oven.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] External atmosphere composition can also influence the aging; hydrogen can diffuse through nickel housing.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Helium can cause similar issues when it diffuses through glass enclosures of rubidium standards.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Gold is a favored electrode material for low-aging resonators; its adhesion to quartz is strong enough to maintain contact even at strong mechanical shocks, but weak enough to not support significant strain gradients (unlike chromium, aluminium, and nickel).
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Gold also does not commonly form oxides; it adsorbs organic contaminants from the air, but these are easy to remove.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] However, gold alone can undergo delamination; a layer of chromium is therefore sometimes used for improved binding strength.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Silver and aluminium are often used as electrodes; however both form oxide layers with time that increases the crystal mass and lowers frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Silver can be passivated by exposure to iodine vapors, forming a layer of silver iodide.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Aluminium oxidizes readily but slowly, until about 5 nm thickness is reached; increased temperature during artificial aging does not significantly increase the oxide forming speed; a thick oxide layer can be formed during manufacture by anodizing.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A DC voltage bias between the electrodes can accelerate the initial aging, probably by induced diffusion of impurities through the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Placing a capacitor in series with the crystal and a several-megaohm resistor in parallel can minimize such voltages.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Aging decreases logarithmically with time, the largest changes occurring shortly after manufacture.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Artificially aging a crystal by prolonged storage at 85 to 125 °C can increase its long-term stability.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] High magnitudes of shocks may tear the crystals off their mountings (especially in the case of large low-frequency crystals suspended on thin wires), or cause cracking of the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals free of surface imperfections are highly shock-resistant; chemical polishing can produce crystals able to survive tens of thousands of g.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals have no inherent failure mechanisms; some have operated in devices for decades.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Failures may be, however, introduced by faults in bonding, leaky enclosures, corrosion, frequency shift by aging, breaking the crystal by too high mechanical shock, or radiation-induced damage when non-swept quartz is used.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals can be also damaged by overdriving.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Crystals suffer from minor short-term frequency fluctuations as well.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The short-term stability is measured by four main parameters: Allan variance (the most common one specified in oscillator data sheets), phase noise, spectral density of phase deviations, and spectral density of fractional frequency deviations.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The effects of acceleration and vibration tend to dominate the other noise sources; surface acoustic wave devices tend to be more sensitive than bulk acoustic wave (BAW) ones, and the stress-compensated cuts are even less sensitive.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The relative orientation of the acceleration vector to the crystal dramatically influences the crystal's vibration sensitivity.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Mechanical vibration isolation mountings can be used for high-stability crystals.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Phase noise plays a significant role in frequency synthesis systems using frequency multiplication; a multiplication of a frequency by N increases the phase noise power by N2.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] A frequency multiplication by 10 times multiplies the magnitude of the phase error by 10 times.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] This can be disastrous for systems employing PLL or FSK technologies.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Magnetic fields have little effect on the crystal itself, as quartz is diamagnetic; eddy currents or AC voltages can however be induced into the circuits, and magnetic parts of the mounting and housing may be influenced.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] After the power-up, the crystals take several seconds to minutes to "warm up" and stabilize their frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The oven-controlled OCXOs require usually 3–10 minutes for heating up to reach thermal equilibrium; the oven-less oscillators stabilize in several seconds as the few milliwatts dissipated in the crystal cause a small but noticeable level of internal heating.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The crystals have to be driven at the appropriate drive level.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Low-frequency crystals, especially flexural-mode ones, may fracture at too high drive levels.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The drive level is specified as the amount of power dissipated in the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] The appropriate drive levels are about 5 μW for flexural modes up to 100 kHz, 1 μW for fundamental modes at 1–4 MHz, 0.5 μW for fundamental modes 4–20 MHz and 0.5 μW for overtone modes at 20–200 MHz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Too low drive level may cause problems with starting the oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Low drive levels are better for higher stability and lower power consumption of the oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p01] Higher drive levels, in turn, reduce the impact of noise by increasing the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] The resonator plate can be cut from the source crystal in many different ways.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] The orientation of the cut influences the crystal's aging characteristics, frequency stability, thermal characteristics, and other parameters.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] These cuts operate at bulk acoustic wave (BAW); for higher frequencies, surface acoustic wave (SAW) devices are employed.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] The letter ‘T’ in the cut name marks a temperature-compensated cut – a cut oriented in a way that the temperature coefficients of the lattice are minimal; the FC and SC cuts are also temperature-compensated.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] Strip resonators, usually AT cuts, are smaller and therefore less sensitive to mechanical shocks.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] At the same frequency and overtone, the strip has less pullability, higher resistance, and higher temperature coefficient.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] The low frequency cuts are mounted at the nodes where they are virtually motionless; thin wires are attached at such points on each side between the crystal and the leads.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] The large mass of the crystal suspended on the thin wires makes the assembly sensitive to mechanical shocks and vibrations.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] The crystals are usually mounted in hermetically sealed glass or metal cases, filled with a dry and inert atmosphere, usually vacuum, nitrogen, or helium.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] Plastic housings can be used as well, but those are not hermetic and another secondary sealing has to be built around the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] Several resonator configurations are possible, in addition to the classical way of directly attaching leads to the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] The gap between the electrodes and the resonator act as two small series capacitors, making the crystal less sensitive to circuit influences.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] The architecture eliminates the effects of the surface contacts between the electrodes, the constraints in the mounting connections, and the issues related to ion migration from the electrodes into the lattice of the vibrating element.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] The resulting configuration is rugged, resistant to shock and vibration, resistant to acceleration and ionizing radiation, and has improved aging characteristics.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] AT cut is usually used, though SC cut variants exist as well.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] BVA resonators are often used in spacecraft applications.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] In the 1930s to 1950s, it was fairly common for people to adjust the frequency of the crystals by manual grinding.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] The crystals were ground using a fine abrasive slurry, or even a toothpaste, to increase their frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] A slight decrease by 1–2 kHz when the crystal was overground was possible by marking the crystal face with a pencil lead, at the cost of a lowered Q.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] The frequency of the crystal is slightly adjustable ("pullable") by modifying the attached capacitances.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] A varactor, a diode with capacitance depending on applied voltage, is often used in voltage-controlled crystal oscillators, VCXO.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] The crystal cuts are usually AT or rarely SC, and operate in fundamental mode; the amount of available frequency deviation is inversely proportional to the square of the overtone number, so a third overtone has only one-ninth of the pullability of the fundamental mode.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] SC cuts, while more stable, are significantly less pullable.
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] On electrical schematic diagrams, *crystals* are designated with the class letter *Y* (Y1, Y2, etc.).
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] Oscillators, whether they are crystal oscillators or others, are designated with the class letter *G* (G1, G2, etc.).
[src:oscillator-circuits/crystal-oscillator-p02] Crystals may also be designated on a schematic with *X* or *XTAL* (a phonetic abbreviation, comparable to using *Xmas* for *Christmas*), or a crystal oscillator with ***XO***.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] An **electronic oscillator** is an electronic circuit that produces a periodic, oscillating or alternating current (AC) signal, usually a sine wave, square wave or a triangle wave, powered by a direct current (DC) source.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Oscillators are found in many electronic devices, such as radio receivers, television sets, radio and television broadcast transmitters, computers, computer peripherals, cellphones, radar, and many other devices.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] There are two general types of electronic oscillators: the **linear** or **harmonic oscillator**, and the **nonlinear** or **relaxation oscillator**.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The two types are fundamentally different in how oscillation is produced, as well as in the characteristic type of output signal that is generated.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The most-common linear oscillator in use is the crystal oscillator, in which the output frequency is controlled by a piezo-electric resonator consisting of a vibrating quartz crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Crystal oscillators are ubiquitous in modern electronics, being the source for the clock signal in computers and digital watches, as well as a source for the signals generated in radio transmitters and receivers.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] As a crystal oscillator's “native” output waveform is sinusoidal, a signal-conditioning circuit may be used to convert the output to other waveform types, such as the square wave typically utilized in computer clock circuits.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The most common form of linear oscillator is an electronic amplifier such as a transistor or operational amplifier connected in a feedback loop with its output fed back into its input through a frequency selective electronic filter to provide positive feedback.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] When the power supply to the amplifier is switched on initially, electronic noise in the circuit provides a non-zero signal to get oscillations started.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The noise travels around the loop and is amplified and filtered until very quickly it converges on a sine wave at a single frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Typical block diagram of a negative resistance oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In some types the negative resistance device is connected in parallel with the resonant circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Negative-resistance oscillators are usually used at high frequencies in the microwave range and above, since at these frequencies feedback oscillators perform poorly due to excessive phase shift in the feedback path.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In negative-resistance oscillators, a resonant circuit, such as an LC circuit, crystal, or cavity resonator, is connected across a device with negative differential resistance, and a DC bias voltage is applied to supply energy.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] A resonant circuit by itself is "almost" an oscillator; it can store energy in the form of electronic oscillations if excited, but because it has electrical resistance and other losses the oscillations are damped and decay to zero.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The negative resistance of the active device cancels the (positive) internal loss resistance in the resonator, in effect creating a resonator circuit with no damping, which generates spontaneous continuous oscillations at its resonant frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The negative-resistance oscillator model is not limited to one-port devices like diodes; feedback oscillator circuits with two-port amplifying devices such as transistors and tubes also have negative resistance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] At high frequencies, three terminal devices such as transistors and FETs are also used in negative resistance oscillators.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] At high frequencies these devices do not need a feedback loop, but with certain loads applied to one port can become unstable at the other port and show negative resistance due to internal feedback.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The negative resistance port is connected to a tuned circuit or resonant cavity, causing them to oscillate.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] High-frequency oscillators in general are designed using negative-resistance techniques.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] A **nonlinear** or **relaxation oscillator** produces a non-sinusoidal output, such as a square, sawtooth or triangle wave.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] It consists of an energy-storing element (a capacitor or, more rarely, an inductor) and a nonlinear switching device (a latch, Schmitt trigger, or negative resistance element) connected in a feedback loop.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The switching device periodically charges the storage element with energy and when its voltage or current reaches a threshold discharges it again, thus causing abrupt changes in the output waveform.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Although in the past negative resistance devices like the unijunction transistor, thyratron tube or neon lamp were used, today relaxation oscillators are mainly built with integrated circuits like the 555 timer IC.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Square-wave relaxation oscillators are used to provide the clock signal for sequential logic circuits such as timers and counters, although crystal oscillators are often preferred for their greater stability.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Triangle-wave or sawtooth oscillators are used in the timebase circuits that generate the horizontal deflection signals for cathode-ray tubes in analogue oscilloscopes and television sets.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] They are also used in voltage-controlled oscillators (VCOs), inverters and switching power supplies, dual-slope analog to digital converters (ADCs), and in function generators to generate square and triangle waves for testing equipment.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In general, relaxation oscillators are used at lower frequencies and have poorer frequency stability than linear oscillators.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Ring oscillators are built of a ring of active delay stages, such as inverters.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Generally the ring has an odd number of inverting stages, so that there is no single stable state for the internal ring voltages.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Instead, a single transition propagates endlessly around the ring.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] An oscillator can be designed so that the oscillation frequency can be varied over some range by an input voltage or current.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] These voltage-controlled oscillators are widely used in phase-locked loops, in which the oscillator's frequency can be locked to the frequency of another oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] These are ubiquitous in modern communications circuits, used in filters, modulators, demodulators, and forming the basis of frequency synthesizer circuits which are used to tune radios and televisions.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Radio frequency VCOs are usually made by adding a varactor diode to the tuned circuit or resonator in an oscillator circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Changing the DC voltage across the varactor changes its capacitance, which changes the resonant frequency of the tuned circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Voltage-controlled relaxation oscillators can be constructed by charging and discharging the energy storage capacitor with a voltage-controlled current source.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Increasing the input voltage increases the rate of charging the capacitor, decreasing the time between switching events.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] A feedback oscillator circuit consists of two parts connected in a feedback loop; an amplifier A and an electronic filter $\beta (j\omega )$ .
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The filter's purpose is to limit the frequencies that can pass through the loop so the circuit only oscillates at the desired frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Since the filter and wires in the circuit have resistance they consume energy and the amplitude of the signal drops as it passes through the filter.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The amplifier is needed to increase the amplitude of the signal to compensate for the energy lost in the other parts of the circuit, so the loop will oscillate, as well as supply energy to the load attached to the output.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The ratio of output to input of the loop, ${v_{o} \over v_{i}}=A\beta (j\omega )$ , is called the loop gain.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] If the loop gain were less than one, the signal would decrease around the loop, resulting in an exponentially decaying sine wave that decreases to zero.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Equations (1) and (2) are called the *Barkhausen stability criterion*.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] It is a necessary but not a sufficient criterion for oscillation, so there are some circuits which satisfy these equations that will not oscillate.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] An equivalent condition often used instead of the Barkhausen condition is that the circuit's closed loop transfer function (the circuit's complex impedance at its output) have a pair of poles on the imaginary axis.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In general, the phase shift of the feedback network increases with increasing frequency so there are only a few discrete frequencies (often only one) which satisfy the second equation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] If the amplifier gain A is high enough that the loop gain is unity (or greater, see Startup section) at one of these frequencies, the circuit will oscillate at that frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Many amplifiers such as common-emitter transistor circuits are "inverting", meaning that their output voltage decreases when their input increases.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In these the amplifier provides 180° phase shift, so the circuit will oscillate at the frequency at which the feedback network provides the other 180° phase shift.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] An alternate mathematical stability test sometimes used instead of the Barkhausen criterion is the Nyquist stability criterion.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] This has a wider applicability than the Barkhausen, so it can identify some of the circuits which pass the Barkhausen criterion but do not oscillate.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Temperature changes, other environmental changes, aging, and manufacturing tolerances will cause component values to "drift" away from their designed values.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Changes in *frequency determining* components such as the tank circuit in LC oscillators will cause the oscillation frequency to change, so for a constant frequency these components must have stable values.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] How stable the oscillator's frequency is to other changes in the circuit, such as changes in values of other components, gain of the amplifier, the load impedance, or the supply voltage, is mainly dependent on the Q factor ("quality factor") of the feedback filter.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Since the *amplitude* of the output is constant due to the nonlinearity of the amplifier (see Startup section below), changes in component values cause changes in the phase shift $\phi \;=\;\angle A\beta (j\omega )$ of the feedback loop.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Since oscillation can only occur at frequencies where the phase shift is a multiple of 360°, $\phi \;=\;360n^{\circ }$ , shifts in component values cause the oscillation frequency $\omega _{0}$ to change to bring the loop phase back to 360n°.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] RC oscillators have the equivalent of a very low Q , so the phase changes very slowly with frequency, therefore a given phase change will cause a large change in the frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In contrast, LC oscillators have tank circuits with high Q (~102).
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] This means the phase shift of the feedback network increases rapidly with frequency near the resonant frequency of the tank circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] So a large change in phase causes only a small change in frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Therefore, the circuit's oscillation frequency is very close to the natural resonant frequency of the tuned circuit, and doesn't depend much on other components in the circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The quartz crystal resonators used in crystal oscillators have even higher Q (104 to 106) and their frequency is very stable and independent of other circuit components.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The frequency of RC and LC oscillators can be tuned over a wide range by using variable components in the filter.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] A microwave cavity can be tuned mechanically by moving one of the walls.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In contrast, a quartz crystal is a mechanical resonator whose resonant frequency is mainly determined by its dimensions, so a crystal oscillator's frequency is only adjustable over a very narrow range, a tiny fraction of one percent.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Its frequency can be changed slightly by using a trimmer capacitor in series or parallel with the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] (1) and (2), merely gives the frequencies at which steady-state oscillation is possible, but says nothing about the amplitude of the oscillation, whether the amplitude is stable, or whether the circuit will start oscillating when the power is turned on.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] A typical rule of thumb is to make the small signal loop gain at the oscillation frequency 2 or 3.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] When the power is turned on, oscillation is started by the power turn-on transient or random electronic noise present in the circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Noise guarantees that the circuit will not remain "balanced" precisely at its unstable DC equilibrium point (Q point) indefinitely.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Due to the narrow passband of the filter, the response of the circuit to a noise pulse will be sinusoidal, it will excite a small sine wave of voltage in the loop.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Since for small signals the loop gain is greater than one, the amplitude of the sine wave increases exponentially.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] During startup, while the amplitude of the oscillation is small, the circuit is approximately linear, so the analysis used in the Barkhausen criterion is applicable.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] When the amplitude becomes large enough that the amplifier becomes nonlinear, generating harmonic distortion, technically the frequency domain analysis used in normal amplifier circuits is no longer applicable, so the "gain" of the circuit is undefined.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] However the filter attenuates the harmonic components produced by the nonlinearity of the amplifier, so the fundamental frequency component $\sin \omega _{0}t$ mainly determines the loop gain (this is the "harmonic balance" analysis technique for nonlinear circuits).
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The sine wave cannot grow indefinitely; in all real oscillators some nonlinear process in the circuit limits its amplitude, reducing the gain as the amplitude increases, resulting in stable operation at some constant amplitude.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In most oscillators this nonlinearity is simply the saturation (limiting or clipping) of the amplifying device, the transistor, vacuum tube or op-amp.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The maximum voltage swing of the amplifier's output is limited by the DC voltage provided by its power supply.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Another possibility is that the output may be limited by the amplifier slew rate.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] As the amplitude of the output nears the power supply voltage rails, the amplifier begins to saturate on the peaks (top and bottom) of the sine wave, flattening or "clipping" the peaks.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] To achieve the maximum amplitude sine wave output from the circuit, the amplifier should be biased midway between its clipping levels.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] For example, an op amp should be biased midway between the two supply voltage rails.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] A common-emitter transistor amplifier's collector voltage should be biased midway between cutoff and saturation levels.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Since the output of the amplifier can no longer increase with increasing input, further increases in amplitude cause the equivalent gain of the amplifier and thus the loop gain to decrease.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] This is a stable equilibrium; if the amplitude of the sine wave increases for some reason, increased clipping of the output causes the loop gain $|A\beta (j\omega _{0})|$ to drop below one temporarily, reducing the sine wave's amplitude back to its unity-gain value.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Similarly if the amplitude of the wave decreases, the decreased clipping will cause the loop gain to increase above one, increasing the amplitude.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] An exception to the above are high Q oscillator circuits such as crystal oscillators; the narrow bandwidth of the crystal removes the harmonics from the output, producing a 'pure' sinusoidal wave with almost no distortion even with large loop gains.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Since oscillators depend on nonlinearity for their operation, the usual linear frequency domain circuit analysis techniques used for amplifiers based on the Laplace transform, such as root locus and gain and phase plots (Bode plots), cannot capture their full behavior.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] To determine startup and transient behavior and calculate the detailed shape of the output waveform, electronic circuit simulation computer programs like SPICE are used.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Component values are tweaked until the simulation results are satisfactory.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The distorted oscillations of real-world (nonlinear) oscillators are called limit cycles and are studied in nonlinear control theory.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In applications where a 'pure' very low distortion sine wave is needed, such as precision signal generators, a nonlinear component is often used in the feedback loop that provides a 'slow' gain reduction with amplitude.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] This stabilizes the loop gain at an amplitude below the saturation level of the amplifier, so it does not saturate and "clip" the sine wave.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Resistor-diode networks and FETs are often used for the nonlinear element.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] An older design uses a thermistor or an ordinary incandescent light bulb; both provide a resistance that increases with temperature as the current through them increases.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] As the amplitude of the signal current through them increases during oscillator startup, the increasing resistance of these devices reduces the loop gain.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The essential characteristic of all these circuits is that the nonlinear gain-control circuit must have a long time constant, much longer than a single period of the oscillation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Therefore, over a single cycle they act as virtually linear elements, and so introduce very little distortion.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The operation of these circuits is somewhat analogous to an automatic gain control (AGC) circuit in a radio receiver.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The Wien bridge oscillator is a widely used circuit in which this type of gain stabilization is used.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] At high frequencies it becomes difficult to physically implement feedback oscillators because of shortcomings of the components.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Since at high frequencies the tank circuit has very small capacitance and inductance, parasitic capacitance and parasitic inductance of component leads and PCB traces become significant.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] These may create unwanted feedback paths between the output and input of the active device, creating instability and oscillations at unwanted frequencies (parasitic oscillation).
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Parasitic feedback paths inside the active device itself, such as the interelectrode capacitance between output and input, make the device unstable.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The input impedance of the active device falls with frequency, so it may load the feedback network.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] As a result, stable feedback oscillators are difficult to build for frequencies above 500 MHz, and negative resistance oscillators are usually used for frequencies above this.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The first practical oscillators were based on electric arcs, which were used for lighting in the 19th century.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Ernst Lecher in 1888 showed that the current through an electric arc could be oscillatory.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] An oscillator was built by Elihu Thomson in 1892 by placing an LC tuned circuit in parallel with an electric arc and included a magnetic blowout.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The arc oscillator was rediscovered and popularized by William Duddell in 1900.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Duddell, a student at London Technical College, was investigating the hissing arc effect.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] He attached an LC circuit (tuned circuit) to the electrodes of an arc lamp, and the negative resistance of the arc excited oscillation in the tuned circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Some of the energy was radiated as sound waves by the arc, producing a musical tone.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Duddell demonstrated his oscillator before the London Institute of Electrical Engineers by sequentially connecting different tuned circuits across the arc to play the national anthem "God Save the Queen".
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Duddell's "singing arc" did not generate frequencies above the audio range.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In 1902 Danish physicists Valdemar Poulsen and P.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Pederson were able to increase the frequency produced into the radio range by operating the arc in a hydrogen atmosphere with a magnetic field, inventing the Poulsen arc radio transmitter, the first continuous wave radio transmitter, which was used through the 1920s.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The vacuum-tube feedback oscillator was invented around 1912, when it was discovered that feedback ("regeneration") in the recently invented audion (triode) vacuum tube could produce oscillations.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] At least six researchers independently made this discovery, although not all of them can be said to have a role in the invention of the oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In the summer of 1912, Edwin Armstrong observed oscillations in audion radio receiver circuits and went on to use positive feedback in his invention of the regenerative receiver.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Austrian Alexander Meissner independently discovered positive feedback and invented oscillators in March 1913.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Irving Langmuir at General Electric observed feedback in 1913.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Fritz Lowenstein may have preceded the others with a crude oscillator in late 1911.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Round patented amplifying and oscillating circuits in 1913.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In August 1912, Lee De Forest, the inventor of the audion, had also observed oscillations in his amplifiers, but he didn't understand the significance and tried to eliminate it until he read Armstrong's patents in 1914, which he promptly challenged.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Armstrong and De Forest fought a protracted legal battle over the rights to the "regenerative" oscillator circuit which has been called "the most complicated patent litigation in the history of radio".
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] De Forest ultimately won before the Supreme Court in 1934 on technical grounds, but most sources regard Armstrong's claim as the stronger one.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The first and most widely used relaxation oscillator circuit, the astable multivibrator, was invented in 1917 by French engineers Henri Abraham and Eugene Bloch.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] They called their cross-coupled, dual-vacuum-tube circuit a *multivibrateur*, because the square-wave signal it produced was rich in harmonics, compared to the sinusoidal signal of other vacuum-tube oscillators.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Vacuum-tube feedback oscillators became the basis of radio transmission by 1920.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] However, the triode vacuum tube oscillator performed poorly above 300 MHz because of interelectrode capacitance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] To reach higher frequencies, new "transit time" (velocity modulation) vacuum tubes were developed, in which electrons traveled in "bunches" through the tube.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The first of these was the Barkhausen–Kurz oscillator (1920), the first tube to produce power in the UHF range.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The most important and widely used were the klystron (R. and S.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Varian, 1937) and the cavity magnetron (J.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Mathematical conditions for feedback oscillations, now called the Barkhausen criterion, were derived by Heinrich Georg Barkhausen in 1921.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] He also showed that all linear oscillators must have negative resistance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] The first analysis of a nonlinear electronic oscillator model, the Van der Pol oscillator, was done by Balthasar van der Pol in 1927.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] He originated the term "relaxation oscillation" and was first to distinguish between linear and relaxation oscillators.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] He showed that the stability of the oscillations (limit cycles) in actual oscillators was due to the nonlinearity of the amplifying device.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] Further advances in mathematical analysis of oscillation were made by Hendrik Wade Bode and Harry Nyquist in the 1930s.
[src:oscillator-circuits/electronic-oscillator] In 1969 Kaneyuki Kurokawa derived necessary and sufficient conditions for oscillation in negative-resistance circuits, which form the basis of modern microwave oscillator design.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The **Hartley oscillator** is an electronic oscillator circuit in which the oscillation frequency is determined by a tuned circuit consisting of capacitors and inductors, that is, an LC oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The circuit was invented in 1915 by American engineer Ralph Hartley.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The distinguishing feature of the Hartley oscillator is that the tuned circuit consists of a single capacitor in parallel with two inductors in series (or a single tapped inductor), and the feedback signal needed for oscillation is taken from the center connection of the two inductors.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The Hartley oscillator was invented by Hartley while he was working for the Research Laboratory of the Western Electric Company.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] Hartley invented and patented the design in 1915 while overseeing Bell System's transatlantic radiotelephone tests; it was awarded patent number 1,356,763 on October 26, 1920.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The original 1915 version used a triode as the amplifying device in common cathode configuration, with three batteries, and separate adjustable coils.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The simplified common-drain JFET circuit diagram uses an LC tank (here the single winding is tapped) and a single battery, but is otherwise essentially the same as the patent drawing.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The Hartley oscillator is the dual of the Colpitts oscillator, which uses two capacitors rather than two inductors for its voltage divider.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] Although there is no requirement for mutual coupling between the two coil segments, the circuit is usually implemented using a tapped coil, with the feedback taken from the tap, as shown here.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The frequency of oscillation is approximately the resonant frequency of the tank circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The actual oscillation frequency will be slightly lower than given above, because of parasitic capacitance in the coil and loading by the transistor.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The output is harmonic-rich if taken from the amplifier and not directly from the LC circuit (unless amplitude-stabilisation circuitry is employed).
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] This may be considered an advantage or a disadvantage.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The schematic shows an example with component values.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The common drain amplifier has a high input impedance and a low output impedance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] Therefore, the amplifier input is connected to the high impedance top of the LC circuit C1, L1, L2 and the amplifier output is connected to the low impedance tap of the LC circuit.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] The grid leak C2 and R1 sets the operating point automatically through grid leak bias.
[src:oscillator-circuits/hartley-oscillator] A smaller value of C2 gives less harmonic distortion, but requires a larger load resistor.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] In signal processing, **phase noise** is the frequency-domain representation of random fluctuations in the phase of a waveform, corresponding to time-domain deviations from perfect periodicity (jitter).
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Generally speaking, radio-frequency engineers speak of the phase noise of an oscillator, whereas digital-system engineers work with the jitter of a clock.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] An ideal oscillator would generate a pure sine wave.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] In the frequency domain, this would be represented as a single pair of Dirac delta functions (positive and negative conjugates) at the oscillator's frequency; i.e., all the signal's power is at a single frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] All real oscillators have phase modulated noise components.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The phase noise components spread the power of a signal to adjacent frequencies, resulting in noise sidebands.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Different phase noise processes, $\phi (t)$ , possess different power Spectral density (PSD).
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] For example, a white noise PSD follows a $f^{0}$ trend, a pink noise PSD follows a $f^{-1}$ trend, and a brown noise PSD follows a $f^{-2}$ trend.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] $\operatorname {S} _{\phi }(f)$ is the single-sided (f>0) **phase noise PSD** $\left[{\frac {rad^{2}}{Hz}}\right]$ , given by the Fourier transform of the Autocorrelation of the phase noise, as stated in the Wiener–Khinchin theorem.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The phase noise can also be given as the **spectral purity**, ${\mathcal {L}}\left(f\right)\left[{\frac {dBc}{Hz}}\right]$ , the single-sideband power in a 1 Hz bandwidth at a frequency offset, f, from the carrier frequency, $f_{0}$ , referenced to the carrier power.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The stochastic dynamics of $\phi (t)$ due to white noise can be understood as a random walk or diffusion process, with a characteristic diffusion coefficient D .
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The variance of $\phi (t)$ grows with time t according to ${\overline {\phi ^{2}(t)}}=2Dt$ , and the PSD of the signal $x(t)$ yields what is described above in case of white noise perturbation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] If phase diffusion is faster (larger D ) for a given signal amplitude A , the PSD becomes wider and shorter, yielding larger phase noise.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The problem of determining the PSD (phase noise) is commensurate with determining D .
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Phase noise is sometimes also measured and expressed as a power obtained by integrating ℒ(*f*) over a certain range of offset frequencies.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] For example, the phase noise may be −40 dBc integrated over the range of 1 kHz to 100 kHz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Phase noise can be measured using a spectrum analyzer if the phase noise of the device under test (DUT) is large with respect to the spectrum analyzer's local oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Care should be taken that observed values are due to the measured signal and not the shape factor of the spectrum analyzer's filters.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Spectrum analyzer based measurement can show the phase-noise power over many decades of frequency; e.g., 1 Hz to 10 MHz.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The slope with offset frequency in various offset frequency regions can provide clues as to the source of the noise; e.g., low frequency flicker noise decreasing at 30 dB per decade (= 9 dB per octave).
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Phase noise measurement systems are alternatives to spectrum analyzers.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] These systems may use internal and external references and allow measurement of both residual (additive) and absolute noise.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Additionally, these systems can make low-noise, close-to-the-carrier, measurements.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The sinusoidal output of an ideal oscillator is a Dirac delta function in the power spectral density centered at the frequency of the sinusoid.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Such perfect spectral purity is not achievable in a practical oscillator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Spreading of the spectrum line caused by phase noise is characterized by the fundamental linewidth and the integral linewidth.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The **fundamental linewidth**, also known as the White noise-limited linewidth or the intrinsic linewidth, is the linewidth of an oscillator's PSD in the presence of only white noise sources (noise with a PSD that follows a $f^{0}$ trend, ie. equivalent across all frequencies).
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The fundamental linewidth takes Lorentzian spectral line shape, and is given by twice the phase diffusion constant, $2D$ (full width, half maximum).
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] White noise provides a $1/{\sqrt {\tau }}$ Allan Deviation plot at small averaging times.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The **integral linewidth**, also known as the effective linewidth or the total linewidth, is the linewidth of an oscillator's PSD in the presence of both white noise sources (noise with a PSD that follows a $f^{0}$ trend) and pink noise sources (noise with a PSD that follows a $f^{-1}$ trend).
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Pink noise is sometimes called Flicker noise, or simply 1/f noise.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The integral linewidth takes Voigt lineshape, a convolution of the white noise-induced Lorentzian lineshape and the pink noise-induced Gaussian lineshape.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Pink noise provides a $\tau ^{0}$ Allan Deviation plot at moderate averaging times.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] This flat line on the Allan Deviation plot is also known as the flicker floor.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Additionally, the oscillator might experience Frequency drift over long periods of time, slowly moving the center frequency of the Voigt lineshape.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] This drift is a brown noise source (noise with a PSD that follows a $f^{-2}$ trend), and provides a ${\sqrt {\tau }}$ Allan Deviation plot at large averaging times.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] A laser is a common oscillator that is characterized by its noise, and thus its Laser linewidth.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The laser noise provides fundamental limitations of the systems that the laser is used in, such as loss of sensitivity in radar and communications systems, lack of definition in imaging systems, and a higher bit error rate in digital systems.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] Lasers with a near-Infrared center wavelength are used in many atomic, molecular, and optical physics experiments to provide photons that interact with atoms.
[src:oscillator-circuits/phase-noise] The requirements for the spectral purity at specific frequency offsets of the lasers used in qubit operation (such as clock transition lasers and state preparation lasers) are highly stringent because the coherence time of the qubit is directly related to the linewidth of the lasers.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A **voltage-controlled oscillator** (**VCO**) is an electronic oscillator whose oscillation frequency is controlled by a voltage input.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The applied input voltage determines the instantaneous oscillation frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Consequently, a VCO can be used for frequency modulation (FM) or phase modulation (PM) by applying a modulating signal to the control input.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A VCO is also an integral part of a phase-locked loop.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] VCOs are used in synthesizers to generate a waveform whose pitch can be adjusted by a voltage determined by a musical keyboard or other input.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A **voltage-to-frequency converter** (**VFC**) is a special type of VCO designed to be very linear in frequency control over a wide range of input control voltages.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] VCOs can be generally categorized into two groups based on the type of waveform produced.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A voltage-controlled capacitor is one method of making an LC oscillator vary its frequency in response to a control voltage.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Any reverse-biased semiconductor diode displays a measure of voltage-dependent capacitance and can be used to change the frequency of an oscillator by varying a control voltage applied to the diode.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Special-purpose variable-capacitance varactor diodes are available with well-characterized, wide-ranging values of capacitance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A varactor is used to change the capacitance (and hence the frequency) of an LC tank.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A varactor can also change the loading on a crystal resonator and pull its resonant frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The same effect occurs with bipolar transistors, as described by Donald E.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Thomas at Bell Labs in 1954: with a tank circuit connected to the collector and the modulating audio signal applied between the emitter and the base, a single-transistor FM transmitter is created.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Thomas worked with a point-contact transistor, but the effect also works in junction transistors; applications include wireless microphones such as that patented by Raymond A.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] For low-frequency VCOs, other methods of varying the frequency (such as altering the charging rate of a capacitor by means of a voltage-controlled current source) are used (see function generator).
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The frequency of a ring oscillator is controlled by varying either the supply voltage, the current available to each inverter stage, or the capacitive loading on each stage.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] VCOs are used in analog applications such as frequency modulation and frequency-shift keying.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The functional relationship between the control voltage and the output frequency for a VCO (especially those used at radio frequency) may not be linear, but over small ranges, the relationship is approximately linear, and linear control theory can be used.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A voltage-to-frequency converter (VFC) is a special type of VCO designed to be very linear over a wide range of input voltages.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Modeling for VCOs is often not concerned with the amplitude or shape (sinewave, triangle wave, sawtooth) but rather its instantaneous phase.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] In effect, the focus is not on the time-domain signal *A* sin(*ωt*+*θ*0) but rather the argument of the sine function (the phase).
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Consequently, modeling is often done in the phase domain.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The instantaneous frequency of a VCO is often modeled as a linear relationship with its instantaneous control voltage.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The output phase of the oscillator is the integral of the instantaneous frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] For analyzing a control system, the Laplace transforms of the above signals are useful.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Tuning range, tuning gain and phase noise are the important characteristics of a VCO.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Generally, low phase noise is preferred in a VCO.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Tuning gain and noise present in the control signal affect the phase noise; high noise or high tuning gain implies more phase noise.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Other important elements that determine the phase noise are sources of flicker noise (1/*f* noise) in the circuit, the output power level, and the loaded Q factor of the resonator.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The low-frequency flicker noise affects the phase noise because the flicker noise is heterodyned to the oscillator output frequency due to the non-linear transfer function of active devices.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The effect of flicker noise can be reduced with negative feedback that linearizes the transfer function (for example, emitter degeneration).
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] VCOs generally have a lower Q factor compared to similar fixed-frequency oscillators, and so suffer more jitter.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The jitter can be made low enough for many applications (such as driving an ASIC), in which case VCOs enjoy the advantages of having no off-chip components (expensive) or on-chip inductors (low yields on generic CMOS processes).
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Commonly used VCO circuits are the Clapp and Colpitts oscillators.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The more widely used oscillator of the two is Colpitts and these oscillators are very similar in configuration.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] In integrated radio transmitters and receivers, cross-coupled LC oscillators are widely used due to their differential output signal, which offers advantages over traditional single-ended topologies such as Clapp and Colpitts oscillators.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A **voltage-controlled crystal oscillator** (**VCXO**) is used for fine adjustment of the operating frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The frequency of a voltage-controlled crystal oscillator can be varied a few tens of parts per million (ppm) over a control voltage range of typically 0 to 3 volts, because the high Q factor of the crystals allows frequency control over only a small range of frequencies.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A **temperature-compensated VCXO** (**TCVCXO**) incorporates components that partially correct the dependence on temperature of the resonant frequency of the crystal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A smaller range of voltage control then suffices to stabilize the oscillator frequency in applications where temperature varies, such as heat buildup inside a transmitter.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Placing the oscillator in a crystal oven at a constant but higher-than-ambient temperature is another way to stabilize oscillator frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] High-stability crystal oscillator references often place the crystal in an oven and use a voltage input for fine control.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The temperature is selected to be the *turnover temperature*: the temperature where small changes do not affect the resonance.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] The control voltage can be used to occasionally adjust the reference frequency to a NIST source.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Sophisticated designs may also adjust the control voltage over time to compensate for crystal aging.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A clock generator is an oscillator that provides a timing signal to synchronize operations in digital circuits.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] VCXO clock generators are used in many areas such as digital TV, modems, transmitters and computers.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Design parameters for a VCXO clock generator are tuning voltage range, center frequency, frequency tuning range and the timing jitter of the output signal.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Jitter is a form of phase noise that must be minimised in applications such as radio receivers, transmitters and measuring equipment.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] When a wider selection of clock frequencies is needed, the VCXO output can be passed through digital divider circuits to obtain lower frequencies or be fed to a phase-locked loop (PLL).
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] ICs containing both a VCXO (for external crystal) and a PLL are available.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A typical application is to provide clock frequencies in a range from 12 to 96 kHz to an audio digital-to-analog converter.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A frequency synthesizer generates precise and adjustable frequencies based on a stable single-frequency clock.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] A digitally controlled oscillator based on a frequency synthesizer may serve as a digital alternative to analog voltage-controlled oscillator circuits.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] VCOs are used in function generators, phase-locked loops, including frequency synthesizers used in communication equipment and the production of electronic music, to generate variable tones in synthesizers.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Function generators are low-frequency oscillators that feature multiple waveforms, typically sine, square, and triangle waves.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Monolithic function generators are voltage-controlled.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Analog phase-locked loops typically contain VCOs.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] High-frequency VCOs are usually used in phase-locked loops for radio receivers.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Phase noise is the most important specification in this application.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Audio-frequency VCOs are used in analog music synthesizers.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] For these, sweep range, linearity, and distortion are often the most important specifications.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Audio-frequency VCOs for use in musical contexts were largely superseded in the 1980s by their digital counterparts, digitally controlled oscillators (DCOs), due to their output stability in the face of temperature changes during operation.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Since the 1990s, musical software has become the dominant sound-generating method.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Voltage-to-frequency converters are voltage-controlled oscillators with a highly linear relation between applied voltage and frequency.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] They are used to convert a slow analog signal (such as from a temperature transducer) to a signal suitable for transmission over a long distance, since the frequency will not drift or be affected by noise.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Oscillators in this application may have sine or square wave outputs.
[src:oscillator-circuits/voltage-controlled-oscillator] Where the oscillator drives equipment that may generate radio-frequency interference, adding a varying voltage to its control input, called dithering, can disperse the interference spectrum to make it less objectionable (see spread-spectrum clock).
